x4freetext: Two GANIL cyclotrons
A 2.7 mg/cm2 polypropylene (CH2)n target (density of
0.896)located at the center of the SPEG scattering
chamber. The target was rotated to an angle of 45.degr.
from the beam axis in order to minimize the energy loss
and angular straggling for low-energy protons.
Here the secondary beams were produced by fragmentation
of a 95 MeV/A 36Ar primary beam, delivered by the GANIL
facility with an intensity of 2 e mu-A, on a 492 mg/cm2
12C target. The beams were purified by traversing a
100 mg/cm2 plastic degrader placed in the dispersive
plane of the alpha spectrometer spectrometer used as a
fragment separator, transported with a momentum
acceptance of 0.6% to the target chamber of the SPEG
spectrometer, and finally focused on the reaction
target.
The scattering angle in the laboratory frame
(THETALab) takes into account the incident angle of
the projectile and its position on the target
measured with the CATS detectors. The recoil energy
is corrected for the average energy loss in the target.
The experimental apparatus
MUST is an array of eight Si-strip detectors backed
by Si(Li) diodes and CsI crystals read out by
photodiodes, placed at 15 cm from the target. The
double sided Si-strip detectors are 6 x 6 cm2 in
size, 300 mu-m thick with 60 strips on each side with a
pitch of 1 mm allowing a localization in horizontal and
vertical directions. The charges created by the passing
through of the incident particle are collected on
aluminum electrodes deposited on the strips.
The Si-strip detectors measured proton energies ranging
from 800 keV to 6 MeV. The Si(Li) detectors have an
active area of 58 x 58 mm2 and an active thickness of
3 mm approximately. Protons with a maximum energy of
25 MeV stop in this detector. The CsI crystal is
60 x 60 x 30 mm thick, tapered from 15 mm high to
18 x 18 mm2, and allows for the measurement of proton
energies up to 70 MeV.
Two position-sensitive detectors - the low
pressure multiwire trajectory chambers CATS ("chambres
a trajectoires de Saclay",  Trajectory Chambers of
Saclay) - were used to improve the definition of the
position of the incoming ion on the target.
The error on the normalization is
estimated to be 10%, taking into account the
background and the error on the target thickness.
Statistical uncertainty
Uncertainty in angle definition
An analysis of the data using phenomenological
optical model potentials (OMPs) is presented. In order
to perform a microscopic OMP analysis a self-consistent
Quasiparticle Random Phase Approximation (QRPA)
model based on a Hartree-Fock+ BCS calculation was
developed. Other scattering calculations using
configuration mixing (CM) densities obtained from
Hartree-Fock-Bogoliubov (HFB) predictions are also
presented and compared with the data.
Data were received from Dr. V.Lapoux
